
1. Objective
The objective of this project is to build a credit risk model to predict the probability that a borrower
will default on a loan. The model outputs a Probability of Default (PD) based on financial and credit
history features.

2. Dataset Description
The dataset contains borrower financial and credit history information including: loan amount,
annual income, total balance, total credit limit, total monthly debt, monthly income, age, past
delinquencies, and default status.

3. Feature Engineering
To enhance predictive performance, additional financial ratios were created:
• Credit Utilization Rate = Total Balance / Total Credit Limit
• Debt-to-Income Ratio (DTI) = Total Monthly Debt / Monthly Income
• Loan-to-Income Ratio = Loan Amount / Annual Income

4. Model Development
Two machine learning models were developed: Logistic Regression and LightGBM. Logistic
Regression was used as a baseline due to its interpretability and common use in credit risk
modeling. LightGBM was used to capture non-linear relationships and improve predictive accuracy.

5. Model Evaluation
Model performance was evaluated using Area Under the ROC Curve (AUC) and Gini coefficient.
AUC measures the model’s ability to distinguish between defaulters and non-defaulters. Gini
coefficient is calculated as: Gini = 2 × AUC − 1.

6. Conclusion
The credit risk model successfully predicts borrower default probability using engineered financial
features. LightGBM generally provides stronger predictive performance, while Logistic Regression
offers interpretability. Such models can support loan approval decisions and risk management
strategies.
